messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /invoices/{id}

All HTTP methods acceptable
- false

HTTP methods acceptable for this endpoint (based on the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation (source lines referenced)
- The router for invoices is mounted in index.js with: app.use('/invoices', invoiceRoutes). That gives the prefix "/invoices".
- In routes/invoices.js the route handling for the path with an id is defined as '/:id':
  - router.get('/:id', getInvoice) → GET /invoices/:id (so GET /invoices/{id} is supported).
  - router.patch('/:id', updateInvoice) → PATCH /invoices/:id (so PATCH /invoices/{id} is supported).
  - router.delete('/:id', deleteInvoice) → DELETE /invoices/:id (so DELETE /invoices/{id} is supported).
- There is no router.put('/:id', ...), router.post('/:id', ...), router.head('/:id', ...), router.options('/:id', ...), or router.trace('/:id', ...) in the code, therefore PUT, POST, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are not declared for this path according to the code.
- The "All HTTP methods acceptable" flag is false because there is no code that registers an all-method handler (e.g., router.all or similar) for this route.
